The shrine is traditionally believed to have been founded during the reign of Emperor Sujin, the 10th emperor of Japan. It is said to have been dedicated to the deities brought from Mount Miwa in Yamato Province. 

In Enryaku 15 (796), the shrine was Ranked as an official shrine along with {{ill|Kamo Shrine (Kiryu)|ja|賀茂神社 (桐生市)|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kamo Shrine (Kiryu)|qq=|1=Kamo Shrine|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q11634952}} (as recorded in the [[:en:Nihon Kōki|Nihon Kōki]]). During the Gangyō period (880), it was awarded the Rank of Senior Fifth Rank, Junior Grade, alongside other local shrines, as documented in the [[:en:Nihon Sandai Jitsuroku|Sandai Jitsuroku]].

According to the {{ill|Jinmyōchō|ja|上野国神名帳|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Jinmyōchō|qq=}}, the shrine was listed as "Miwa Daimyōjin of First Rank." Unfortunately, during the Tenshō era, a fire destroyed many of the shrine's old records and treasures.

Historically, the temple {{ill|Enmanji (Kiryu)|ja|円満寺 (桐生市)|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Enmanji (Kiryu)|qq=|1=Enman-ji|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q11394812}} served as its bettō-ji (attached temple). During the Edo period, the local Kojima family managed both the shrine and its associated temple.

In Meiji 5 (1872), the shrine was officially designated as a Gōsha (local shrine). In 1908, the [[:en:Yasaka Shrine|Yasaka Shrine (Kiryu)]] of Honmachi 3-chome, previously dedicated to Gozu Tenno and attached to Shujōin Temple, was merged into Miwa Shrine.

