'''Miwa Shrine''' (美和神社, *Miwa Jinja*) is a [[:en:Shinto shrine|Shinto shrine]] located in Miyamoto-chō, Kiryu City, Gunma Prefecture, Japan. It is listed as a minor {{ill|2=ja|Shikinaisha|ja|式内社|1=Shikinaisha|2=ja|3=式内社|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/2=ja|13=User:Immanuelle|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|2=ja|3=延喜式神名帳|4=zh|5=延喜式神名帳|6=simple|7=Engishiki Jinmyocho|lt=Shikinaisha}} and was formerly Ranked as a {{ill|2=ja|Gōsha|ja|郷社|1=Gō-sha|qid=Q134917316}}{{efn|District Shrines|lt=Ken-sha|1=modern system of ranked Shinto shrines|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/2=ja|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to JA|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q712534}} under the old shrine Ranking system.

==Overview==
Miwa Shrine enshrines {{ill|2=ja|Ōmononushi Kushi-mika-tama-no-Mikoto|ja|大物主櫛甕玉命|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/2=ja|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to JA}} and {{ill|2=ja|Takehayasusanoo-no-Mikoto|ja|武速須佐之男命|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/2=ja|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to JA}}. It is situated at the southeastern foot of Mount Agatsuma in Kiryu, facing Yamate-dori Avenue. The shrine is known for hosting performances of [[:en:Kagura|Kagura]] and taiko drumming during the annual {{ill|2=ja|Kiryu Ebisu Festival|ja|桐生ゑびす講|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/2=ja|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to JA|1=Kiryū Nishinomiya Shrine|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q11537354}} held from November 19–20. A mikoshi (portable shrine) storehouse for the {{ill|2=ja|Kiryu Yagibushi Festival|ja|桐生八木節まつり|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/2=ja|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to JA|1=Kiryū Yagibushi festival|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q11537271}} is located adjacent to the worship hall.

==History==
Miwa Shrine is traditionally said to have been established during the reign of Emperor Sujin, with its deity transferred from Mount Miwa in Yamato Province. It was officially recognized as a shrine in 796 (Enryaku 15) alongside [[:en:Kamo shrines|Kamo Shrine]]. In 880 (Gangyō 4), it was awarded the Rank of Senior Fifth Rank, Lower Grade, alongside other shrines such as [[:en:Kamo shrines|Kamo Shrine]], {{ill|2=ja|Kohachisu Shrine|ja|甲波宿禰社|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/2=ja|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to JA}}, and {{ill|2=ja|Oiwai Shrine|ja|小祝社|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/2=ja|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to JA}}.

The shrine was referred to as "Conferred First Rank Miwa Daimyōjin" in the {{ill|2=ja|Kōzuke no Kuni Jinmyōchō|ja|上野国神名帳|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/2=ja|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to JA}}. Unfortunately, it lost many of its historical records and treasures in a fire during the Tenshō era.

Miwa Shrine was originally affiliated with {{ill|2=ja|Enman-ji Temple|ja|円満寺|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/2=ja|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to JA}}, and both were managed by the Kojima family during the Edo period. It was designated as a Gōsha in 1872 (Meiji 5) and merged with the former [[:en:Yasaka Shrine|Yasaka Shrine]] in 1908 (Meiji 41).

==Sub-Shrines==
* '''Yasaka Shrine''' – Former Village shrine, merged in 1908
* '''Yagokoro-omoikane Shrine''' – Former precinct shrine of Yasaka Shrine
* '''Hata Shrine''' – Former precinct shrine of Yasaka Shrine
* '''Ichigami Shrine (Horinwa Gongen)''' – Former precinct shrine of Yasaka Shrine
* '''Matsuo Shrine'''
* '''Kotohira Shrine'''
* '''Nishinomiya Shrine'''

