[[File:Miwa-jinja (Kiryu), haiden-1.jpg|250px]]<br/>Worship Hall

== Overview ==

'''Miwa Shrine''' (美和神社) is located in {{ill|Miyamoto Town, Kiryu|ja|宮本町 (桐生市)|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Miyamoto Town, Kiryu|qq=|1=Miyamoto-chō|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q11454887}}, Kiryu City, Gunma Prefecture, Japan. It is a {{ill|Shikinaisha|ja|式内社|1=Shikinaisha|2=ja|3=式内社|qq=draft|1=Shikinaisha|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shikinaisha|13=User:Immanuelle|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|2=ja|3=延喜式神名帳|4=zh|5=延喜式神名帳|6=simple|7=Engishiki Jinmyocho|lt=Shikinaisha}}, Ranked as a "small shrine," and was previously designated as a Gōsha (local shrine) under the [[:en:Modern system of ranked Shinto shrines|Modern system of Ranked Shinto shrines]].

The shrine venerates the deities [[:en:Ōmononushi|Ōmononushi]] (Ōmononushi Kushi Mikatama no Mikoto) and [[:en:Susanoo-no-Mikoto|Susanoo-no-Mikoto]] (Takesu Susanoo no Mikoto).

== History ==

The shrine is traditionally believed to have been founded during the reign of Emperor Sujin, the 10th emperor of Japan. It is said to have been dedicated to the deities brought from Mount Miwa in Yamato Province. 

In Enryaku 15 (796), the shrine was Ranked as an official shrine along with {{ill|Kamo Shrine (Kiryu)|ja|賀茂神社 (桐生市)|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kamo Shrine (Kiryu)|qq=|1=Kamo Shrine|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q11634952}} (as recorded in the [[:en:Nihon Kōki|Nihon Kōki]]). During the Gangyō period (880), it was awarded the Rank of Senior Fifth Rank, Junior Grade, alongside other local shrines, as documented in the [[:en:Nihon Sandai Jitsuroku|Sandai Jitsuroku]].

According to the {{ill|Jinmyōchō|ja|上野国神名帳|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Jinmyōchō|qq=}}, the shrine was listed as "Miwa Daimyōjin of First Rank." Unfortunately, during the Tenshō era, a fire destroyed many of the shrine's old records and treasures.

Historically, the temple {{ill|Enmanji (Kiryu)|ja|円満寺 (桐生市)|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Enmanji (Kiryu)|qq=|1=Enman-ji|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q11394812}} served as its bettō-ji (attached temple). During the Edo period, the local Kojima family managed both the shrine and its associated temple.

In Meiji 5 (1872), the shrine was officially designated as a Gōsha (local shrine). In 1908, the [[:en:Yasaka Shrine|Yasaka Shrine (Kiryu)]] of Honmachi 3-chome, previously dedicated to Gozu Tenno and attached to Shujōin Temple, was merged into Miwa Shrine.

== Sub-Shrines (境内社) ==

* Yasaka Shrine – Previously a village shrine, merged in 1908.
* Yaokotonashi Shrine – Former sub-shrine of Yasaka Shrine.
* Kikami Shrine – Former sub-shrine of Yasaka Shrine.
* Ichigami Shrine (Hōrinkan Gongen) – Former sub-shrine of Yasaka Shrine.
* Matsuo Shrine
* Kotohira Shrine
* {{ill|Kiryu Nishinomiya Shrine|ja|桐生西宮神社|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kiryu Nishinomiya Shrine|qq=|1=Kiryū Nishinomiya Shrine|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q11537354}}

== Cultural Events ==

The shrine is the center of the {{ill|Kiryu Ebisu Festival|ja|桐生ゑびす講|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kiryu Ebisu Festival|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 桐生西宮神社|1=Kiryū Nishinomiya Shrine|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q11537354}}, held annually from November 19 to 20. It features Kagura dances and taiko drum performances. Additionally, the shrine is involved in the {{ill|Kiryu Yagibushi Festival|ja|桐生八木節まつり|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kiryu Yagibushi Festival|qq=|1=Kiryū Yagibushi festival|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q11537271}}, where its mikoshi (portable shrine) is stored in an adjacent warehouse.

